        "title": "2. State-machine logic (`handleKey`) — untested, and the highest-risk gap",
        "content": "\n`handleKey` (tui.go:147) drives all three screens. No test exercises cursor bounds, selection toggling, the limit-parsing branch, or quit/cancel wiring.\n\nMissing scenarios:\n- `screenPicking`: cursor doesn't go below 0 or above `len(providers)-1`; space toggles; `a` selects all; `enter` with nothing selected auto-selects all and transitions to `screenLimit`; `enter` with a partial selection preserves it.\n- `screenLimit`: `esc` returns to `screenPicking` without side effects; `enter` with a non-numeric value is a no-op (doesn't crash, doesn't transition); `enter` with a negative value is rejected; `enter` with `\"0\"` is accepted (explicitly valid — unlimited); `enter` with valid value transitions to `screenRunning` and calls `startRun` (spawns goroutines — needs a fake/interceptable crawler, see §4).\n- `q`/`ctrl+c` from any screen calls `cancel()` if set and returns `tea.Quit` — currently untested that `cancel` is actually invoked (regression risk: forgetting to call `m.cancel()` would leak subprocesses silently).\n\n```go\nfunc TestHandleKey_Picking_CursorBounds(t *testing.T) {\n\tm := newModel(10, \"../crawler\")\n\tm.screen = screenPicking\n\tm.handleKey(keyMsg(\"up\")) // already at 0\n\tif m.cursor != 0 {\n\t\tt.Fatalf(\"cursor should clamp at 0, got %d\", m.cursor)\n\t}\n\tfor range providers {\n\t\tm.handleKey(keyMsg(\"down\"))\n\t}\n\tif m.cursor != len(providers)-1 {\n\t\tt.Fatalf(\"cursor should clamp at %d, got %d\", len(providers)-1, m.cursor)\n\t}\n}\n\nfunc TestHandleKey_Picking_EnterWithNoneSelectsAll(t *testing.T) {\n\tm := newModel(10, \"../crawler\")\n\tm.screen = screenPicking\n\tm.handleKey(keyMsg(\"enter\"))\n\tif m.screen != screenLimit {\n\t\tt.Fatalf(\"expected transition to screenLimit\")\n\t}\n\tif m.countSelected() != len(providers) {\n\t\tt.Fatalf(\"expected all providers selected, got %d\", m.countSelected())\n\t}\n}\n\nfunc TestHandleKey_Limit_RejectsInvalidInput(t *testing.T) {\n\tm := newModel(10, \"../crawler\")\n\tm.screen = screenLimit\n\tm.limitInput.SetValue(\"-5\")\n\tm.handleKey(keyMsg(\"enter\"))\n\tif m.screen != screenLimit {\n\t\tt.Fatalf(\"negative limit should not advance screen\")\n\t}\n\tm.limitInput.SetValue(\"not-a-number\")\n\tm.handleKey(keyMsg(\"enter\"))\n\tif m.screen != screenLimit {\n\t\tt.Fatalf(\"non-numeric limit should not advance screen\")\n\t}\n}\n\nfunc TestHandleKey_Quit_CallsCancel(t *testing.T) {\n\tcalled := false\n\tm := newModel(10, \"../crawler\")\n\tm.cancel = func() { called = true }\n\tm.handleKey(keyMsg(\"q\"))\n\tif !called {\n\t\tt.Fatalf(\"expected cancel() to be invoked on quit\")\n\t}\n}\n\n// keyMsg is a tiny helper to build tea.KeyMsg for known key strings in tests\n// (bubbletea's tea.KeyMsg construction requires mapping a string like \"up\"/\"enter\"\n// to a tea.KeyType — add this helper once, alongside the test file).\n```\n\n",
        "level": 3
      },
      {
        "title": "3. `Update()` message routing — untested",
        "content": "\n`Update` (tui.go:99) branches on `statusMsg`, `doneMsg`, `spinner.TickMsg`, `tea.WindowSizeMsg`. None are exercised. Specific gaps:\n- `statusMsg` for a provider that **isn't** the currently highlighted one should *not* trigger `refreshViewport()` (currently unverified — a bug here wouldn't be caught).\n- `doneMsg` with a non-nil `err` sets `stateError` and appends `\"error: ...\"` to `lines`; with nil `err` sets `stateDone` and appends nothing. Neither branch is tested.\n- `m.pending` decrements exactly once per `doneMsg` — no test guards against double-decrement or drift.\n- **Potential nil-pointer risk, untested**: `statusMsg`/`doneMsg` both do `st := m.statuses[msg.provider]` and then dereference `st.state` without a nil check. If a message ever arrives for a provider not present in `m.statuses` (e.g. a stray/late message from a previous run), this panics. No test currently proves this can't happen, and no defensive code guards it — flag as a real gap for either a test that pins current behavior or a nil-guard.\n\n```go\nfunc TestUpdate_DoneMsg_Success(t *testing.T) {\n\tm := newModel(10, \"../crawler\")\n\tm.runOrder = []string{\"midi-madagasikara\"}\n\tm.statuses[\"midi-madagasikara\"] = &providerStatus{state: stateRunning}\n\tm.pending = 1\n\tm.Update(doneMsg{provider: \"midi-madagasikara\", err: nil})\n\tst := m.statuses[\"midi-madagasikara\"]\n\tif st.state != stateDone || m.pending != 0 {\n\t\tt.Fatalf(\"got state=%v pending=%d\", st.state, m.pending)\n\t}\n}\n\nfunc TestUpdate_DoneMsg_Error(t *testing.T) {\n\tm := newModel(10, \"../crawler\")\n\tm.runOrder = []string{\"midi-madagasikara\"}\n\tm.statuses[\"midi-madagasikara\"] = &providerStatus{state: stateRunning}\n\tm.pending = 1\n\twantErr := errors.New(\"boom\")\n\tm.Update(doneMsg{provider: \"midi-madagasikara\", err: wantErr})\n\tst := m.statuses[\"midi-madagasikara\"]\n\tif st.state != stateError || len(st.lines) != 1 || !strings.Contains(st.lines[0], \"boom\") {\n\t\tt.Fatalf(\"unexpected state after error doneMsg: %+v\", st)\n\t}\n}\n\nfunc TestUpdate_StatusMsg_UnknownProvider_Panics(t *testing.T) {\n\t// Documents current behavior: a statusMsg for a provider absent from\n\t// m.statuses panics via nil-pointer dereference. If this is fixed with\n\t// a guard, this test should be replaced with one asserting no panic.\n\tdefer func() {\n\t\tif r := recover(); r == nil {\n\t\t\tt.Fatalf(\"expected panic for unknown provider — update this test if a nil-guard was added\")\n\t\t}\n\t}()\n\tm := newModel(10, \"../crawler\")\n\tm.Update(statusMsg{provider: \"does-not-exist\", line: \"x\"})\n}\n```\n\n",
        "level": 3
      },
      {
        "title": "4. `runCrawler` / `runHeadless` — no error-handling or integration tests, and not currently testable in isolation",
        "content": "\nThis is the biggest structural gap. `runCrawler` (main.go:63) hardcodes `exec.CommandContext(ctx, \"uv\", \"run\", \"main.py\", ...)` — there's no seam to substitute a fake binary, so today the *only* way to test it is a real integration test against a stub script, or a refactor to inject the command name/args.\n\nUntested behavior:\n- `onLine` is called once per stdout **and** stderr line (merged stream) — not verified.\n- Non-zero exit from the child process surfaces as `cmd.Wait()`'s error — not verified.\n- Cancelling `ctx` kills the whole process group via `SIGKILL` on `-cmd.Process.Pid`, not just the `uv` process — this is the most safety-critical piece of code in the file (documented in the comment as a fix for orphaned processes) and has **no coverage at all**. A regression here would silently leak Python crawler processes.\n- `runHeadless` fans out one goroutine per provider and waits for all — no test proves partial failures (`provider A` errors, `provider B` succeeds) don't block or drop the others.\n\nRecommended approach: extract an interface so tests can substitute a fake command, e.g.:\n\n```go\n// Minimal refactor to make this testable — replace the hardcoded exec.CommandContext\n// call with an injectable function, defaulting to the real one in production.\nvar execCommand = exec.CommandContext\n\nfunc runCrawler(ctx context.Context, name string, limit int, crawlerDir string, onLine func(string)) error {\n\tcmd := execCommand(ctx, \"uv\", \"run\", \"main.py\", name, \"--limit\", fmt.Sprint(limit))\n\t// ...unchanged...\n}\n```\n\nThen, integration-style tests using a real shell script stand-in:\n\n```go\nfunc TestRunCrawler_StreamsStdoutAndStderr(t *testing.T) {\n\t// Requires a test fixture script e.g. testdata/fake_main.sh that echoes\n\t// known lines to stdout and stderr, invoked in place of \"uv run main.py\".\n\tdir := t.TempDir()\n\tscript := filepath.Join(dir, \"main.py\") // or swap execCommand entirely\n\tos.WriteFile(script, []byte(\"#!/bin/sh\\necho out-line\\necho err-line >&2\\n\"), 0755)\n\n\tvar got []string\n\tvar mu sync.Mutex\n\terr := runCrawler(context.Background(), \"fake\", 1, dir, func(line string) {\n\t\tmu.Lock()\n\t\tgot = append(got, line)\n\t\tmu.Unlock()\n\t})\n\tif err != nil {\n\t\tt.Fatalf(\"unexpected error: %v\", err)\n\t}\n\tif len(got) != 2 {\n\t\tt.Fatalf(\"expected 2 lines, got %v\", got)\n\t}\n}\n\nfunc TestRunCrawler_NonZeroExit_ReturnsError(t *testing.T) {\n\t// fixture script that `exit 1`s\n\t// assert runCrawler returns a non-nil error\n}\n\nfunc TestRunCrawler_ContextCancel_KillsProcessGroup(t *testing.T) {\n\t// fixture script that spawns a child (or sleeps long) so the test can assert\n\t// that cancelling ctx actually terminates the *group*, not just the direct child —\n\t// e.g. spawn, cancel, then poll `pgrep -g <pgid>` or check no leftover process.\n}\n\nfunc TestRunHeadless_PartialFailureDoesNotBlockOthers(t *testing.T) {\n\t// two fake providers, one exits non-zero, one succeeds — assert both onLine\n\t// outputs get printed and runHeadless returns after both finish (via wg.Wait()).\n}\n```\n\n",
        "level": 3
      },
      {
        "title": "5. `View()` rendering functions — no snapshot/golden tests",
        "content": "\n`viewPicking`, `viewLimit`, `viewRunning` (tui.go:322-434) are entirely untested. Because they emit ANSI-styled strings via lipgloss, exact-match golden tests are brittle across lipgloss versions/terminal profiles — better to assert on **plain-text content** via `lipgloss.NewStyle()`-stripped output or by checking `strings.Contains` on stable substrings (provider names, counts, key hints), rather than full-string equality.\n\n```go\nfunc TestViewPicking_ShowsAllProviderNames(t *testing.T) {\n\tm := newModel(10, \"../crawler\")\n\tout := m.viewPicking()\n\tfor _, p := range providers {\n\t\tif !strings.Contains(out, p) {\n\t\t\tt.Errorf(\"viewPicking() missing provider %q\", p)\n\t\t}\n\t}\n}\n\nfunc TestViewRunning_SummaryCounts(t *testing.T) {\n\tm := newModel(10, \"../crawler\")\n\tm.runOrder = []string{\"midi-madagasikara\", \"lexpress-mg\"}\n\tm.statuses[\"midi-madagasikara\"] = &providerStatus{state: stateDone}\n\tm.statuses[\"lexpress-mg\"] = &providerStatus{state: stateError}\n\tm.vp = viewport.New(40, 10)\n\tout := m.viewRunning()\n\tif !strings.Contains(out, \"1 done\") || !strings.Contains(out, \"1 err\") {\n\t\tt.Errorf(\"viewRunning() summary incorrect:\\n%s\", out)\n\t}\n}\n```\n\n",
        "level": 3
      },
      {
        "title": "6. Missing error-handling tests specifically",
        "content": "\n| Path | Current handling | Test coverage |\n|---|---|---|\n| `strconv.Atoi` failure in `handleKey` (limit input) | silently ignored (`return m, nil`) | none |\n| negative limit | silently ignored | none |\n| `runCrawler` → `cmd.StdoutPipe()` error | propagated as `err` | none |\n| `runCrawler` → `cmd.Start()` error | propagated as `err` | none |\n| `runCrawler` → `cmd.Wait()` non-zero exit | propagated as `err` | none |\n| `p.Run()` error in `main()` | printed to stderr, `os.Exit(1)` | none (would need a `main`-level integration/process test, low priority) |\n| unknown provider in `statusMsg`/`doneMsg` | nil-pointer panic (see §3) | none — undefined behavior today |\n\n",
        "level": 3
      },
      {
        "title": "7. Integration test gaps",
        "content": "\n- **No end-to-end test** exercises `headless` mode against a real (or faked) crawler dir end to end — `-providers`, `-limit`, `-crawler-dir` flag combinations are unverified.\n- **No test verifies the `providers` list stays in sync** with `apps/crawler/providers.py` (explicitly called out as a manual sync point in the comment at main.go:18-20) — a drift-detection test would catch this automatically, e.g. a test (marked to skip if the Python file isn't reachable) that parses `PROVIDERS` keys from `apps/crawler/providers.py` and diffs against the Go `providers` slice.\n\n```go\nfunc TestProvidersListMatchesCrawler(t *testing.T) {\n\tpyPath := filepath.Join(\"..\", \"crawler\", \"providers.py\")\n\tdata, err := os.ReadFile(pyPath)\n\tif err != nil {\n\t\tt.Skipf(\"crawler providers.py not found: %v\", err)\n\t}\n\t// parse PROVIDERS dict keys from data (regex or simple scan) and compare\n\t// set-equality against the `providers` slice in main.go.\n}\n```\n\n",
        "level": 3
      },
      {
        "title": "Priority order to close these gaps",
        "content": "1. Pure functions (`truncate`, `articlesSaved`, `countSelected`, `layout`, `highlighted`) — trivial, immediate value, zero refactor needed.\n2. `handleKey` state-machine tests — second highest value, no refactor needed, catches the majority of UI logic bugs.\n3. Fix and test the nil-pointer risk in `Update()` for unknown providers (§3) — decide: guard defensively, or pin current panic behavior intentionally.\n4. Refactor `runCrawler` for an injectable command (§4), then add subprocess-cancellation tests — this protects the single most safety-critical behavior in the codebase (no orphaned Python crawlers).\n5. `View()` content-assertion tests — lower priority, mostly regression insurance.\n6. Provider-list drift test against `apps/crawler/providers.py` — cheap insurance against the documented manual-sync footgun.",
        "level": 3
      }
    ],
